QUERY: When should I use parallel tool calls?
============================================================
ANSWER: Based on the provided context, parallel tool calls can help you avoid wasteful "back and forth" interactions with Claude [3]. 

The context shows an example where a user asks "What's the weather and time in San Francisco?" but Claude returns only a single tool call for weather initially, even though both pieces of information were requested [3]. After processing that result, Claude then makes a second tool call to get the time [3]. 

The context notes that "while this technically happened immediately, this is potentially wasteful because it required 'back and forth' – first Claude asked for the weather, then we had to process it, and _then_ Claude asked for the time, and now we have to process _that_" [3].

Therefore, you should use parallel tool calls when you want to encourage Claude to make multiple related tool calls simultaneously so you can process them at the same time, rather than having to handle them sequentially [3].

However, the context also indicates that Claude 3.7 Sonnet may be less likely to make parallel tool calls even when parallel tool use is not disabled, and recommends using a "batch tool" workaround [2].

